  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Know Your Customer (KYC) Regulations\n- Collecting detailed customer information\n- Assessing customer risk profiles\n- Ongoing monitoring of customer activities\n\n4. Compliance with Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Laws\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act regulations\n- Implementing internal control systems\n- Training staff on AML procedures\n\n5. Risk Assessment\n- Identifying potential money laundering risks\n- Developing risk mitigation strategies\n- Conducting periodic risk assessments\n\n6. International Cooperation\n- Sharing information with law enforcement\n- Participating in global anti-money laundering efforts\n- Adhering to international financial standards\n\nFailure to comply with these obligations can result in significant legal penalties, fines, and potential loss of banking licenses.",
